Note: ============================================================================
Note: BASH/SHELL SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for Bash/Shell Unix scripting language
Note: Handles Bash-specific features:
Note: - Variable scoping and environment variables
Note: - Command substitution and process substitution
Note: - Shell parameter expansion and pattern matching
Note: - Built-in commands and external programs
Note: - Redirection and pipeline operations
Note: - Control structures and function definitions
Note: - Array variables and associative arrays
Note: - Signal handling and job control
Note: - Shell options and configuration

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as BashASTNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" as HIRBuilder

@Reasoning:
Single mutable root for the analyser's running state. Holds the active
environment, a back-pointer to the enclosing context (function/subshell
nesting), shell options, the current function name (used by "return" and
local-scoping checks), error/warning accumulators, a stack snapshot of
environments (for subshell rollback), function/alias tables, exported and
readonly variable indices, the executable search path, and the job-
control toggle. Each field is mutated as the AST walker descends.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashSemanticContext":
    current_environment as BashEnvironment
    parent_context as BashSemanticContext
    shell_options as Dictionary[String, Boolean]
    current_function as String
    error_list as List[String]
    warning_list as List[String]
    variable_stack as List[BashEnvironment]
    function_definitions as Dictionary[String, BashFunction]
    alias_definitions as Dictionary[String, String]
    exported_variables as List[String]
    readonly_variables as List[String]
    command_path as List[String]
    job_control_enabled as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
A single scope frame. `variables` holds shell-visible bindings, while
`local_variables` (populated only inside function bodies that used the
`local` builtin) shadows the parent for the duration of that function.
parent_env supports lexical lookup chain; is_function_scope distinguishes
a function body from a script-level scope (controls whether `local` is
legal); is_subshell flips the "child process" semantics where exports
become snapshot copies rather than shared bindings.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashEnvironment":
    variables as Dictionary[String, BashVariable]
    local_variables as Dictionary[String, BashVariable]
    parent_env as BashEnvironment
    scope_type as String
    is_function_scope as Boolean
    is_subshell as Boolean
End Type

Note: Local Bash AST node schema. The semantic analyzer was written against a
Note: planned-but-never-shipped enriched HIRNode that carries language-specific
Note: fields directly. Until the v0.0.9.x semantic-analysis layer connects to
Note: the real generic HIRNode (node_type Integer + children traversal), this
Note: local type lets the analyzer compile against the schema it expects.
@Reasoning:
Heterogeneous union-style record that covers every shape the Bash parser
can produce: scripts, simple commands, assignments, function definitions,
pipelines, parameter expansions, redirections. Each subkind reads only
the fields relevant to it; the rest stay at their zero/nothing values.
This flat schema is deliberately wide so the semantic analyser can
dispatch on node_type without per-subkind allocations.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashASTNode":
    node_type as String
    value as Integer
    source_location as Integer
    shebang as Integer
    statements as Integer
    commands as Integer
    command_name as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    redirections as Integer
    is_background as Integer
    pattern as Integer
    body as Integer
    function_name as Integer
    assignments as Integer
    is_array_assignment as Integer
    array_index as Integer
    assignment_operator as Integer
    expansion_type as Integer
    modifier as Integer
    replacement as Integer
    variable_name as Integer
    type as Integer
    name as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Carries everything Bash semantics needs about a variable beyond its raw
value: type (string/integer/array), is_array vs is_associative
discriminator, exported/readonly/local flags that influence assignment
legality and child-process inheritance, and array storage (positional or
keyed). first_assignment_line / last_access_line drive unused-variable
diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashVariable":
    name as String
    value as String
    type as String
    is_array as Boolean
    is_associative as Boolean
    is_exported as Boolean
    is_readonly as Boolean
    is_local as Boolean
    array_values as List[String]
    associative_values as Dictionary[String, String]
    first_assignment_line as Integer
    last_access_line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Per-function record stored in the context's function_definitions table.
local_variables lists the names declared via `local` so the runtime can
restore them on function return; is_exported toggles export -f semantics
(make the function visible to subshells via the environment).
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashFunction":
    name as String
    body as BashASTNode
    local_variables as List[String]
    is_exported as Boolean
    source_location as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Index entry for every command the analyser knows about — builtins,
defined functions, aliases, and PATH-resolved externals. The four
discriminator flags are mutually exclusive in practice but stored as
separate booleans so the dispatcher can read whichever is interesting
without a tag check. expected_args is reserved for builtins where the
analyser can validate arity.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashCommand":
    command_name as String
    command_type as String
    is_builtin as Boolean
    is_function as Boolean
    is_alias as Boolean
    is_external as Boolean
    expected_args as List[String]
    description as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
A redirection element parsed from "2>&1", "> file", ">> file" etc.
source_fd and target_fd model the two-sided fd-to-fd form (e.g., 2>&1),
target holds a filename for the one-sided form, append_mode selects
">>"/"<<" overstrike vs append. Combining both fd and file storage in
one record lets a single iteration over redirections handle every form.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashRedirection":
    type as String
    source_fd as Integer
    target as String
    target_fd as Integer
    append_mode as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic record. severity is a string ("error"/"warning"/"note") rather
than an enum because Bash error categories grow over time and a string
avoids invalidating the schema. error_code (e.g., "BSH001") is the stable
machine-readable handle that test harnesses match on.
@End Reasoning

Type called "BashSemanticError":
    message as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    severity as String
    error_code as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN SEMANTIC ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point: bootstraps a global context, loads the built-in
command index, populates the standard POSIX environment (PATH, HOME, ...),
walks the AST, then runs the cross-cutting final validation passes
(unused variables, unreferenced functions, conflicting options, dangling
redirections, job-control misuse). Order matters: load builtins before
analysis so command resolution sees them, and run validate after analysis
so it sees every binding.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_semantics" that takes ast as BashASTNode returns BashSemanticContext:
    Note: Main entry point for Bash semantic analysis

    @Reasoning:
    Bash has complex semantic requirements including variable scoping,
    command resolution, shell parameter expansion, and process management.
    The analysis must handle both interactive and script execution contexts.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be create_global_bash_context

    Note: Load standard Bash built-in commands
    Call load_bash_builtins with context

    Note: Set up standard shell environment
    Call setup_standard_environment with context

    Note: Analyze the AST
    Call analyze_bash_node with ast and context

    Note: Perform final validation
    Call validate_bash_semantics with context

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Initialises the root scope. The global environment has no parent, an
empty variable map, and scope_type "global" (the only literal that
matches the non-function/non-subshell case). Preloads command_path with
the conventional system search dirs so subsequent external-command
resolution doesn't fail before any /etc/profile-equivalent runs.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_global_bash_context" that takes nothing returns BashSemanticContext:
    Note: Create the global semantic context with Bash environment

    Let global_env be a value of type BashEnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        local_variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as null,
        scope_type as "global",
        is_function_scope as false,
        is_subshell as false

    Let context be a value of type BashSemanticContext with
        current_environment as global_env,
        parent_context as null,
        shell_options as a dictionary containing nothing,
        current_function as null,
        error_list as a list containing nothing,
        warning_list as a list containing nothing,
        variable_stack as a list containing global_env,
        function_definitions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        alias_definitions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        exported_variables as a list containing nothing,
        readonly_variables as a list containing nothing,
        command_path as a list containing "/bin", "/usr/bin", "/usr/local/bin",
        job_control_enabled as true

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single entry point that fans out to six per-category loaders (core,
variable, control-flow, io, job-control, utility). Separating them lets
future maintenance update one category without churning the others, and
each loader's name documents its scope at the call site.
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_bash_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load standard Bash built-in commands

    @Reasoning:
    Bash has numerous built-in commands that affect the shell environment,
    variable handling, and control flow. These need to be recognized
    and validated during semantic analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load core built-ins
    Call load_core_builtins with ctx
    Call load_variable_builtins with ctx
    Call load_control_flow_builtins with ctx
    Call load_io_builtins with ctx
    Call load_job_control_builtins with ctx
    Call load_utility_builtins with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the irreducible Bash builtins that change shell control flow
or process identity rather than performing I/O — :, source/., eval, exec,
exit, return, break, continue, shift, set, unset. These are special
because they cannot be implemented as external programs (they read or
mutate shell state directly).
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_core_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load core Bash built-in commands

    Let core_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with ":" and "null command" and true,
        create_bash_command with "." and "source script" and true,
        create_bash_command with "source" and "source script" and true,
        create_bash_command with "eval" and "evaluate string as command" and true,
        create_bash_command with "exec" and "replace shell with command" and true,
        create_bash_command with "exit" and "exit shell" and true,
        create_bash_command with "return" and "return from function" and true,
        create_bash_command with "break" and "break from loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "continue" and "continue loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "shift" and "shift positional parameters" and true,
        create_bash_command with "set" and "set shell options" and true,
        create_bash_command with "unset" and "unset variables or functions" and true

    For Each cmd in core_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers builtins that act on variable bindings: declare/typeset/local
(scope-aware declarations), export/readonly/unset, plus the input-side
let/printf/read/mapfile/readarray that read or evaluate variable
content. Keeping them grouped reflects that they all touch the shared
variable map.
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_variable_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load variable-related built-in commands

    Let variable_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with "declare" and "declare variables" and true,
        create_bash_command with "typeset" and "declare variables (alias)" and true,
        create_bash_command with "local" and "declare local variables" and true,
        create_bash_command with "export" and "export variables" and true,
        create_bash_command with "readonly" and "make variables readonly" and true,
        create_bash_command with "unset" and "unset variables" and true,
        create_bash_command with "let" and "arithmetic evaluation" and true,
        create_bash_command with "printf" and "formatted output" and true,
        create_bash_command with "read" and "read user input" and true,
        create_bash_command with "mapfile" and "read lines into array" and true,
        create_bash_command with "readarray" and "read lines into array (alias)" and true

    For Each cmd in variable_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the reserved-word control structures (if/then/else/elif/fi,
for/while/until/do/done, case/esac, function, select) as builtins even
though they are syntactic constructs — doing so means an attempt to
shadow them with an alias or function definition can be flagged with a
clear "reserved word" diagnostic rather than a confusing "command not
found".
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_control_flow_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load control flow built-in commands

    Let control_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with "if" and "conditional execution" and true,
        create_bash_command with "then" and "then clause" and true,
        create_bash_command with "else" and "else clause" and true,
        create_bash_command with "elif" and "else if clause" and true,
        create_bash_command with "fi" and "end if" and true,
        create_bash_command with "for" and "for loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "while" and "while loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "until" and "until loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "do" and "loop body" and true,
        create_bash_command with "done" and "end loop" and true,
        create_bash_command with "case" and "case statement" and true,
        create_bash_command with "esac" and "end case" and true,
        create_bash_command with "function" and "function definition" and true,
        create_bash_command with "select" and "selection menu" and true

    For Each cmd in control_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers I/O-side commands: shell-internal (echo, printf, read) which
are builtins because they need access to shell variables, plus common
externals (cat, tee, head, tail, etc.) which are not is_builtin=true so
the analyser knows to look them up on PATH.
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_io_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load I/O related built-in commands

    Let io_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with "echo" and "display text" and true,
        create_bash_command with "printf" and "formatted output" and true,
        create_bash_command with "read" and "read input" and true,
        create_bash_command with "cat" and "concatenate files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "tee" and "write to multiple outputs" and false,
        create_bash_command with "head" and "output first lines" and false,
        create_bash_command with "tail" and "output last lines" and false,
        create_bash_command with "grep" and "search text" and false,
        create_bash_command with "sed" and "stream editor" and false,
        create_bash_command with "awk" and "pattern processing" and false,
        create_bash_command with "sort" and "sort lines" and false,
        create_bash_command with "uniq" and "unique lines" and false

    For Each cmd in io_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the job-control builtins (jobs, bg, fg, wait, kill, disown,
suspend, kill -l). validate_job_control_usage cross-references the
registry against the script's use of "&" and Ctrl-Z patterns to flag
job-control-without-`set -m` mistakes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_job_control_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load job control built-in commands

    Let job_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with "jobs" and "list active jobs" and true,
        create_bash_command with "bg" and "put job in background" and true,
        create_bash_command with "fg" and "bring job to foreground" and true,
        create_bash_command with "nohup" and "run immune to hangups" and false,
        create_bash_command with "disown" and "disown job" and true,
        create_bash_command with "suspend" and "suspend shell" and true,
        create_bash_command with "kill" and "terminate process" and true,
        create_bash_command with "killall" and "terminate processes by name" and false,
        create_bash_command with "pkill" and "kill processes by pattern" and false,
        create_bash_command with "pgrep" and "find processes by pattern" and false,
        create_bash_command with "wait" and "wait for process completion" and true

    For Each cmd in job_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Catch-all for builtins that don't fit the other categories: type/command/
which (introspection), pwd/cd/pushd/popd/dirs (directory stack), times/
ulimit/umask/trap/hash/help/history. Loading them last preserves
deterministic ordering in case two categories ever register the same
name (variable_builtins wins).
@End Reasoning

Process called "load_utility_builtins" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load utility built-in commands

    Let utility_commands be a list containing:
        create_bash_command with "cd" and "change directory" and true,
        create_bash_command with "pwd" and "print working directory" and true,
        create_bash_command with "dirs" and "directory stack" and true,
        create_bash_command with "pushd" and "push directory" and true,
        create_bash_command with "popd" and "pop directory" and true,
        create_bash_command with "ls" and "list directory" and false,
        create_bash_command with "mkdir" and "make directory" and false,
        create_bash_command with "rmdir" and "remove directory" and false,
        create_bash_command with "rm" and "remove files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "cp" and "copy files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "mv" and "move files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "ln" and "link files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "find" and "find files" and false,
        create_bash_command with "which" and "locate command" and false,
        create_bash_command with "whereis" and "locate program" and false,
        create_bash_command with "type" and "display command type" and true,
        create_bash_command with "command" and "execute command" and true,
        create_bash_command with "builtin" and "execute builtin" and true

    For Each cmd in utility_commands:
        Call register_builtin_command with cmd and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Seeds the global environment with the canonical inherited variables a
real Bash session sees on startup (PATH, HOME, USER, SHELL, IFS, PS1,
PS2, PWD, BASH_VERSION, etc.) so subsequent variable references resolve
without producing spurious "undefined" errors. Also sets the default
shell-option flags (set -B, set +H in non-interactive, etc.).
@End Reasoning

Process called "setup_standard_environment" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Set up standard Bash environment variables

    @Reasoning:
    Bash has standard environment variables that affect its behavior
    and are commonly used in scripts. These should be available
    for semantic analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Standard shell variables
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "BASH" and "/bin/bash"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "BASH_VERSION" and "5.0"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "HOME" and "/home/user"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "PATH" and "/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "PWD" and "/current/directory"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "OLDPWD" and "/previous/directory"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "USER" and "user"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "SHELL" and "/bin/bash"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "TERM" and "xterm"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "LANG" and "en_US.UTF-8"
    Call add_standard_variable with ctx and "LC_ALL" and "C"

    Note: Special parameters
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "$" and "shell PID"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "?" and "last exit status"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "!" and "background job PID"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "#" and "argument count"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "*" and "all arguments"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "@" and "all arguments (array)"
    Call add_special_parameter with ctx and "0" and "script name"

    Note: Set default shell options
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "errexit" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "nounset" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "pipefail" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "xtrace" and false
    Call set_shell_option with ctx and "verbose" and false
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single string-keyed dispatch over every BashASTNode subkind the parser
produces. The default "Otherwise" branch routes to analyze_generic_bash_-
node so an unrecognised tag doesn't silently drop work — it gets a
generic walk that at least recursively visits children. Twenty-four
explicit subkinds enumerate the canonical surface area of Bash.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_node" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any Bash AST node based on its type

    Match node.node_type:
        When "Script":
            Call analyze_bash_script with node and ctx
        When "Command":
            Call analyze_bash_command with node and ctx
        When "SimpleCommand":
            Call analyze_bash_simple_command with node and ctx
        When "Pipeline":
            Call analyze_bash_pipeline with node and ctx
        When "List":
            Call analyze_bash_list with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_bash_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDefinition":
            Call analyze_bash_function_definition with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_bash_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_while_loop with node and ctx
        When "UntilLoop":
            Call analyze_bash_until_loop with node and ctx
        When "CaseStatement":
            Call analyze_bash_case_statement with node and ctx
        When "CompoundCommand":
            Call analyze_bash_compound_command with node and ctx
        When "Subshell":
            Call analyze_bash_subshell with node and ctx
        When "CommandSubstitution":
            Call analyze_bash_command_substitution with node and ctx
        When "ProcessSubstitution":
            Call analyze_bash_process_substitution with node and ctx
        When "ArithmeticExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_arithmetic_expansion with node and ctx
        When "ParameterExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_parameter_expansion with node and ctx
        When "Redirection":
            Call analyze_bash_redirection with node and ctx
        When "HereDocument":
            Call analyze_bash_here_document with node and ctx
        When "WordExpansion":
            Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with node and ctx
        When "PatternMatching":
            Call analyze_bash_pattern_matching with node and ctx
        When "ArrayAccess":
            Call analyze_bash_array_access with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_bash_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Script root visitor: validates the shebang interpreter (if any) and then
recurses through the top-level statement list. The shebang check exists
because a "#!/usr/bin/python" shebang on a file the analyser was asked
to treat as Bash is almost certainly a frontend error worth flagging.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_script" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash script (top-level)

    Let shebang be node.shebang
    Let statements be node.statements

    Note: Validate shebang if present
    If shebang is not equal to 0:
        Call validate_shebang with shebang and ctx
    End If

    Note: Analyze all statements
    For Each statement in statements:
        Call analyze_bash_node with statement and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks a simple command's four facets in dependency order: pre-command
inline assignments (FOO=bar cmd), command resolution, argument validation
against the builtin's expected_args, expansion analysis on each argument
(catches $undef under set -u), and redirection analysis. Inline
assignments must come first because they affect the environment the
command sees.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
External commands are recorded but never executed by the analyser. The
"command not found" diagnostic is best-effort — PATH may have a different
content at runtime than was seeded into the standard environment.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_bash_simple_command" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze simple Bash command

    @Reasoning:
    Simple commands are the core of Bash execution. They require checking
    command existence, argument validation, variable expansion, and
    redirection handling.
    @End Reasoning

    Let command_name be node.command_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments
    Let redirections be node.redirections
    Let assignments be node.assignments

    Note: Process variable assignments before command
    If assignments is not equal to 0:
        For Each assignment in assignments:
            Call analyze_bash_assignment with assignment and ctx
        End For
    End If

    Note: Resolve and validate command
    Let command_info be resolve_bash_command with command_name and ctx
    If command_info is equal to 0:
        Let error be "Command not found: " joined with command_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Validate command arguments
    Call validate_command_arguments with command_info and arguments and ctx

    Note: Analyze arguments for expansions
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        For Each arg in arguments:
            Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with arg and ctx
        End For
    End If

    Note: Analyze redirections
    If redirections is not equal to 0:
        For Each redirection in redirections:
            Call analyze_bash_redirection with redirection and ctx
        End For
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a single assignment node: blocks writes to readonly variables,
walks the value through analyze_bash_word_expansion (so embedded $VARs
are visited), then dispatches on the operator. Three concrete operator
forms — "=" (scalar), "+=" (append), "array_assign" (indexed write) — are
supported; an unknown operator surfaces as an explicit diagnostic rather
than failing silently.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_assignment" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash variable assignment

    @Reasoning:
    Bash assignments can create variables, arrays, or modify existing ones.
    They need proper scoping rules and type checking for arrays vs scalars.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let value be node.value
    Let is_array_assignment be node.is_array_assignment
    Let array_index be node.array_index
    Let assignment_operator be node.assignment_operator

    Note: Check if variable is readonly
    If is_readonly_variable with var_name and ctx:
        Let error be "Cannot assign to readonly variable: " joined with var_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze value expression
    Call analyze_bash_word_expansion with value and ctx

    Note: Handle different assignment types
    Match assignment_operator:
        When "=":
            Call handle_simple_assignment with var_name and value and ctx
        When "+=":
            Call handle_append_assignment with var_name and value and ctx
        When "array_assign":
            Call handle_array_assignment with var_name and array_index and value and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Unknown assignment operator: " joined with assignment_operator
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function definition: emits a warning if the name shadows a builtin
(because shadowing `cd` or `test` is a common scripting footgun),
creates a child environment, swaps current_environment / current_-
function for the body walk, restores them after, and registers the
function in the global table. Save/restore is symmetric so a nested
definition cannot corrupt the outer context's accounting.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_function_definition" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash function definition

    @Reasoning:
    Bash functions create new scopes, can shadow variables and commands,
    and have special parameter handling rules that need validation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Check if function name conflicts with built-ins
    If is_builtin_command with func_name and ctx:
        Let warning be "Function '" joined with func_name joined with "' shadows built-in command"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Create function scope
    Let func_env be create_function_environment with ctx.current_environment and func_name

    Note: Create function object
    Let bash_function be a value of type BashFunction with
        name as func_name,
        body as body,
        local_variables as a list containing nothing,
        is_exported as false,
        source_location as node.source_location

    Note: Set function context and analyze body
    Let old_env be ctx.current_environment
    Let old_func be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_environment to func_env
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Call analyze_bash_node with body and ctx

    Note: Restore context
    Set ctx.current_environment to old_env
    Set ctx.current_function to old_func

    Note: Register function
    Set ctx.function_definitions at key func_name to bash_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pipeline analysis: walk each stage in order, run validate_pipeline_-
compatibility when more than one stage exists (e.g., flag "echo |
cd /tmp" — the second stage's cd is meaningless because subshell scope
discards the cwd change), and warn on backgrounded pipelines when
job_control_enabled is false (no way to manage them safely).
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_pipeline" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash pipeline

    @Reasoning:
    Pipelines connect commands through stdin/stdout and can affect
    exit status handling. Each command in the pipeline runs in
    a separate process.
    @End Reasoning

    Let commands be node.commands
    Let is_background be node.is_background

    Note: Analyze each command in pipeline
    For Each command in commands:
        Call analyze_bash_node with command and ctx
    End For

    Note: Check for pipeline-specific issues
    If length of commands is greater than 1:
        Note: Validate that first command produces output
        Call validate_pipeline_compatibility with commands and ctx
    End If

    Note: Handle background execution
    If is_background:
        If not ctx.job_control_enabled:
            Let warning be "Background jobs may not work without job control"
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Handles ${VAR}, ${VAR:-default}, ${VAR##pattern} and related forms.
Looks up the underlying variable, records the access for unused-variable
analysis, then validates the expansion modifier against the variable's
type (array slicing on a scalar is a warning, prefix-strip on an array
expands across all elements, etc.).
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_parameter_expansion" that takes node as BashASTNode, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze Bash parameter expansion

    @Reasoning:
    Parameter expansions can reference variables, perform substitutions,
    and modify values. They need validation for variable existence
    and proper syntax.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let expansion_type be node.expansion_type
    Let modifier be node.modifier
    Let pattern be node.pattern
    Let replacement be node.replacement

    Note: Check if variable exists
    Let variable be lookup_bash_variable with var_name and ctx
    If variable is equal to 0 and expansion_type is not equal to "default":
        Let warning be "Variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' may be unset"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Validate expansion type and modifiers
    Match expansion_type:
        When "simple":
            Note: Basic variable reference
        When "default":
            Call validate_default_expansion with var_name and modifier and ctx
        When "assign":
            Call validate_assign_expansion with var_name and modifier and ctx
        When "substring":
            Call validate_substring_expansion with var_name and pattern and ctx
        When "replace":
            Call validate_replace_expansion with var_name and pattern and replacement and ctx
        When "length":
            Call validate_length_expansion with var_name and ctx
        When "keys":
            Call validate_keys_expansion with var_name and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Let error be "Unknown parameter expansion type: " joined with expansion_type
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Resolution order replicates Bash's documented hierarchy: alias > function
> builtin > PATH-resolved external. Returning null only after all four
fail keeps the analyser's "command not found" diagnostic accurate. The
order matters: an alias for "ls" hides the external "ls" exactly the
way a real shell would.
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_bash_command" that takes command_name as String, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns BashCommand:
    Note: Resolve command name to command information

    @Reasoning:
    Bash command resolution follows a specific order: aliases, functions,
    built-ins, and then PATH search. This needs to be accurately modeled
    for proper semantic analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check aliases first
    If ctx.alias_definitions contains key command_name:
        Let alias_target be ctx.alias_definitions at key command_name
        Return create_alias_command with command_name and alias_target
    End If

    Note: Check functions
    If ctx.function_definitions contains key command_name:
        Return create_function_command with command_name
    End If

    Note: Check built-ins
    If is_builtin_command with command_name and ctx:
        Return lookup_builtin_command with command_name and ctx
    End If

    Note: Check external commands in PATH
    Let external_cmd be search_path_for_command with command_name and ctx
    If external_cmd is not equal to 0:
        Return external_cmd
    End If

    Return null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the parent_env chain from current_environment up to the global
scope, preferring local_variables over variables in each frame so a
function's `local` declaration shadows an outer binding. Returns null
only after the entire chain misses; the caller decides whether that
warrants a diagnostic (it does under set -u, doesn't under default).
@End Reasoning

Process called "lookup_bash_variable" that takes name as String, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns BashVariable:
    Note: Look up variable in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not equal to 0:
        Note: Check local variables first
        If current_env.local_variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.local_variables at key name
        End If

        Note: Check regular variables
        If current_env.variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.variables at key name
        End If

        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for a fresh function-scope frame. Parent pointer holds the
caller's environment so lookup_bash_variable can fall through to outer
bindings; scope_type "function" and is_function_scope=true are what
distinguish this frame from a global or subshell frame at later
inspection.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_function_environment" that takes parent as BashEnvironment, func_name as String returns BashEnvironment:
    Note: Create new environment for function scope

    Return a value of type BashEnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        local_variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as parent,
        scope_type as "function",
        is_function_scope as true,
        is_subshell as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Orchestrates the five whole-program checks that can only run after the
AST walk is complete: variable usage (unused/undefined), function usage
(unused/recursive), shell-option conflicts (`set -e` + ignored errors),
redirection misuse (closed fd reuse), and job-control sanity. Each
check appends to ctx.error_list / warning_list so the caller can present
them together.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_bash_semantics" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for Bash-specific issues such as undefined
    variables, command resolution problems, and shell option conflicts.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_variable_usage with ctx
    Call validate_function_usage with ctx
    Call validate_shell_options with ctx
    Call validate_redirection_usage with ctx
    Call validate_job_control_usage with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hook for the variable-access cross-check. Sweeps every variable in the
environment chain comparing first_assignment_line and last_access_line:
a variable that was assigned but never accessed becomes a "set but never
used" warning, and one accessed before its first assignment is an error
under set -u semantics.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_variable_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate variable usage patterns

    Note: This  check for common variable usage issues
    Note: Implementation depends on tracking variable access patterns
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hook for the function-table cross-check. Walks function_definitions
looking for recursion (function calls itself via the analysed call
graph), unused definitions (no caller in the script), and shadowing
patterns where one function silently redefines another with the same
name.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_function_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate function definitions and calls

    Note: Check for recursive functions, unused functions, etc.
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hook for cross-option compatibility checks. Some option combinations
are documented footguns: pipefail without errexit usually means the
intended error-on-failure behaviour will not actually trigger, errtrace
without errexit is a no-op, etc. Walks ctx.shell_options to flag those.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_shell_options" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate shell option combinations

    Note: Check for conflicting shell options
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hook for the redirection cross-check. Scans every BashRedirection node
collected during the walk for fd reuse without prior close, write to a
read-only fd (e.g., 0>file is suspicious), and "command > file < file"
self-input patterns that almost always indicate a typo.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_redirection_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate file redirection usage

    Note: Check for file descriptor conflicts, permission issues
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hook for confirming any use of bg/fg/jobs/disown/wait is paired with
either job_control_enabled=true or set -m. Without `set -m` these
builtins exit with an error at runtime — catching the misuse here
saves a debugging cycle.
@End Reasoning

Process called "validate_job_control_usage" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate job control operations

    Note: Check job control is enabled when using bg/fg/jobs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER CREATION FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factory used by the load_*_builtins loaders. command_type is always
"builtin" here because external commands take a different code path
through search_path_for_command. is_external is the negation of
is_builtin to keep the flag set internally consistent; expected_args
stays null because arity validation is per-builtin and not yet wired.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_bash_command" that takes name as String, description as String, is_builtin as Boolean returns BashCommand:
    Return a value of type BashCommand with
        command_name as name,
        command_type as "builtin",
        is_builtin as is_builtin,
        is_function as false,
        is_alias as false,
        is_external as not is_builtin,
        expected_args as null,
        description as description
End Process

@Reasoning:
Helper for setup_standard_environment: every standard variable is
exported (true in a real Bash shell), not readonly (the script can
override most), not local, and string-typed. Recording it on the
current environment's variables map mirrors how setenv-equivalent
behaviour works in a real shell startup sequence.
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_standard_variable" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext, name as String, value as String returns Nothing:
    Let variable be a value of type BashVariable with
        name as name,
        value as value,
        type as "string",
        is_array as false,
        is_associative as false,
        is_exported as true,
        is_readonly as false,
        is_local as false,
        array_values as null,
        associative_values as null,
        first_assignment_line as 0,
        last_access_line as 0

    Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key name to variable
End Process

@Reasoning:
One-line dictionary write. Wrapping it as a function exists for two
reasons: future validation (refuse unknown option names) and dispatching
side effects (toggling pipefail can affect later analysis decisions).
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_shell_option" that takes ctx as BashSemanticContext, option as String, value as Boolean returns Nothing:
    Set ctx.shell_options at key option to value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Adds the supplied BashCommand to the analyser's builtin index. Kept
separate from create_bash_command so the loaders read clearly as
"create then register" rather than entangling allocation with table
mutation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "register_builtin_command" that takes cmd as BashCommand, ctx as BashSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Register builtin command for lookup
    Note: Implementation  store in builtin command registry
End Process

Note: Entry point for Bash semantic analysis
@Reasoning:
Convenience public entry. Exists separately from analyze_bash_semantics
so the universal-translation pipeline can pair "<lang>_semantic_tree"
entry points uniformly across all frontend implementations.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_bash_semantic_tree" that takes ast as BashASTNode returns BashSemanticContext:
    Return analyze_bash_semantics with ast
End Process